summary: Gill opposes federal clean energy programs he views as part of a 'globalist climate agenda' and has taken legislative action to abolish the Office of Clean Energy Demonstrations (OCED), arguing for 'unleashing American energy production' and restoring 'energy freedom.' He supports removing statutory authority and federal funding for OCED as part of promoting domestic energy production over federal clean energy demonstrations. He has also praised policies and rhetoric emphasizing 'energy independence' as part of an 'America First' agenda led by President Trump, indicating support for prioritizing domestic energy production and independence. At his January 3, 2025 swearing-in he reiterated a pledge to 'unleash American energy' as an immediate priority.

Has cosponsored clean-energy and climate-related legislation such as the Clean Energy Workforce Act and bills aimed at ending polluter subsidies, signaling support for transitioning to clean energy, workforce development in that sector, and reducing fossil-fuel industry welfare.

Advocates rolling back restrictions on domestic energy production; supported H.R.1 language and messaging claiming to 'end the Radical Leftâ€™s War on American Energy Production.' Also led the bipartisan repeal of a Biden Administration Department of Energy regulation that would have banned non-condensing tankless water heaters made at a local Rinnai facility, and welcomed Secretary of Energy Chris Wright to the plant to celebrate saving local manufacturing jobs, tour the assembly line, and underscore opposition to burdensome energy-related regulations that threaten domestic production.
